20/* The x86_64 ABI specifies both XF and TF modes.
21 XFmode is __float80 is IEEE extended; TFmode is __float128
22 is IEEE quad. */
23
24FRACTIONAL_FLOAT_MODE (XF, 80, 12, ieee_extended_intel_96_format);
25FLOAT_MODE (TF, 16, ieee_quad_format);
26
27/* In ILP32 mode, XFmode has size 12 and alignment 4.
28 In LP64 mode, XFmode has size and alignment 16. */
29ADJUST_FLOAT_FORMAT (XF, (TARGET_128BIT_LONG_DOUBLE
30 ? &ieee_extended_intel_128_format
31 : TARGET_96_ROUND_53_LONG_DOUBLE
32 ? &ieee_extended_intel_96_round_53_format
33 : &ieee_extended_intel_96_format));
34ADJUST_BYTESIZE (XF, TARGET_128BIT_LONG_DOUBLE ? 16 : 12);
35ADJUST_ALIGNMENT (XF, TARGET_128BIT_LONG_DOUBLE ? 16 : 4);
36
37/* Add any extra modes needed to represent the condition code.
38
39 For the i386, we need separate modes when floating-point
40 equality comparisons are being done.
41
42 Add CCNO to indicate comparisons against zero that requires
43 Overflow flag to be unset. Sign bit test is used instead and
44 thus can be used to form "a&b>0" type of tests.
45
46 Add CCGC to indicate comparisons against zero that allows
47 unspecified garbage in the Carry flag. This mode is used
48 by inc/dec instructions.
49
50 Add CCGOC to indicate comparisons against zero that allows
51 unspecified garbage in the Carry and Overflow flag. This
52 mode is used to simulate comparisons of (a-b) and (a+b)
53 against zero using sub/cmp/add operations.
54
55 Add CCA to indicate that only the Above flag is valid.
56 Add CCC to indicate that only the Carry flag is valid.
57 Add CCO to indicate that only the Overflow flag is valid.
58 Add CCP to indicate that only the Parity flag is valid.
59 Add CCS to indicate that only the Sign flag is valid.
60 Add CCZ to indicate that only the Zero flag is valid. */
61
62CC_MODE (CCGC);
63CC_MODE (CCGOC);
64CC_MODE (CCNO);
65CC_MODE (CCA);
66CC_MODE (CCC);
67CC_MODE (CCO);
68CC_MODE (CCP);
69CC_MODE (CCS);
70CC_MODE (CCZ);
71CC_MODE (CCFP);
72CC_MODE (CCFPU);
73
74/* Vector modes. Note that VEC_CONCAT patterns require vector
75 sizes twice as big as implemented in hardware. */
76VECTOR_MODES (INT, 4); /* V4QI V2HI */
77VECTOR_MODES (INT, 8); /* V8QI V4HI V2SI */
78VECTOR_MODES (INT, 16); /* V16QI V8HI V4SI V2DI */
79VECTOR_MODES (INT, 32); /* V32QI V16HI V8SI V4DI */
80VECTOR_MODES (INT, 64); /* V64QI V32HI V16SI V8DI */
81VECTOR_MODES (INT, 128); /* V128QI V64HI V32SI V16DI */
82VECTOR_MODES (FLOAT, 8); /* V2SF */
83VECTOR_MODES (FLOAT, 16); /* V4SF V2DF */
84VECTOR_MODES (FLOAT, 32); /* V8SF V4DF V2TF */
85VECTOR_MODES (FLOAT, 64); /* V16SF V8DF V4TF */
86VECTOR_MODES (FLOAT, 128); /* V32SF V16DF V8TF */
87VECTOR_MODES (FLOAT, 256); /* V64SF V32DF V16TF */
88VECTOR_MODE (INT, TI, 1); /* V1TI */
89VECTOR_MODE (INT, DI, 1); /* V1DI */
90VECTOR_MODE (INT, SI, 1); /* V1SI */
91VECTOR_MODE (INT, QI, 2); /* V2QI */
92VECTOR_MODE (INT, QI, 12); /* V12QI */
93VECTOR_MODE (INT, QI, 14); /* V14QI */
94VECTOR_MODE (INT, HI, 6); /* V6HI */
95VECTOR_MODE (INT, SI, 64); /* V64SI */
96
97POINTER_BOUNDS_MODE (BND32, 8);
98POINTER_BOUNDS_MODE (BND64, 16);
99
100INT_MODE (OI, 32);
101INT_MODE (XI, 64);
102
103/* Keep the OI and XI modes from confusing the compiler into thinking
104 that these modes could actually be used for computation. They are
105 only holders for vectors during data movement. */
106#define MAX_BITSIZE_MODE_ANY_INT (128)
107
108/* The symbol Pmode stands for one of the above machine modes (usually SImode).
109 The tm.h file specifies which one. It is not a distinct mode. */
110
